{"author":{"id":"cc8322a500b8739c77faac347808f6026d9ccb7880d0aaa7ad76754163cd7fdb"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1782568927,"nonce":"MovuqkZbFWOLQucG647A2wuTwaY=","kind":"plan","title":"kref cranky-review remediation + grouped help â€” Implementation Plan"},{"type":3,"timestamp":1782568927,"nonce":"WoU5TW/vjNquV8fsbdHN/OF2U04=","body":"# kref cranky-review remediation + grouped help â€” Implementation Plan\n\n\u003e **For agentic workers:** REQUIRED SUB-SKILL: Use superpowers:subagent-driven-development (recommended) or superpowers:executing-plans to implement this plan task-by-task. Steps use checkbox (`- [ ]`) syntax for tracking.\n\n**Goal:** Close the eleven findings in `.test-output/cranky-review-2026-06-18.md` and add a grouped/ordered `--help`, per `docs/dev/specs/2026-06-18-cranky-review-remediation-design.md`.\n\n**Architecture:** A Go CLI (`spf13/cobra`) over git-bug's `entity/dag`. Changes touch the CLI wiring (`cmd/kref`), the entry op-DAG (`internal/entry`), the store (`internal/store`), the ingest bridge and hooks (`internal/bridge`, `internal/hooks`), and docs. Each finding is an independent commit; docs-only and additive changes first, behavior changes last.\n\n**Tech Stack:** Go â‰Ą1.26.4 (via `GOTOOLCHAIN=auto`), cobra v1.10.2, Ginkgo v2 + Gomega, gitleaks (runtime), `task`.\n\n**Conventions:** Tests are Ginkgo/Gomega only; `internal/entry` specs are black-box `package entry_test`, other packages white-box. Run tests with `task test` (provisions gitleaks + sets `KREF_GITLEAKS`). Bare `go test` needs `KREF_GITLEAKS=$(go env GOPATH)/bin/gitleaks`. The committed `bin/kref` may be non-executable under this sandbox's SELinux label â€” build to a temp path to exercise the CLI manually.\n\n---\n\n## Task 1: README â€” fix the `.kref/` store-directory wording (P1)\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `README.md` (ingest section, ~line 112-113)\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Replace the misleading sentence**\n\nFind:\n\n```\ningest fails closed so the secret never reaches that entry's tier.\n`--skip-missing` skips paths that do not exist. The store directory (`.kref/`) is\ngitignored, so materialized copies never get committed to your code history.\n```\n\nReplace with:\n\n```\ningest fails closed so the secret never reaches that entry's tier.\n`--skip-missing` skips paths that do not exist. Entries live in git refs\n(`refs/kref-{private,personal,shared}/*`), not on disk. `kref init` also gitignores\n`.kref/`, a directory **reserved** for a future materialized-view feature\n(`kref checkout`, see the design spec); it is not created or used today.\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Verify no other prose calls `.kref/` \"the store directory\"**\n\nRun: `grep -n 'store directory' README.md`\nExpected: no matches.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add README.md\ngit commit -m \"docs: stop calling .kref/ the store; entries live in git refs\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 2: README â€” caveat the `go install` path (P1)\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `README.md` (install section, ~line 52-57)\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Add the caveat**\n\nFind:\n\n```\nOr `go install` (then ensure `gitleaks` is on `PATH`, or set `KREF_GITLEAKS`):\n\n```bash\ngo install github.com/riotbox/kref/cmd/kref@latest\n```\n```\n\nReplace with:\n\n```\nOr, **once the repository is public and a release is tagged**, `go install`\n(then ensure `gitleaks` is on `PATH`, or set `KREF_GITLEAKS`):\n\n```bash\ngo install github.com/riotbox/kref/cmd/kref@latest\n```\n\nUntil then, use the source build above â€” `@latest` cannot resolve an\nunpublished/untagged module.\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add README.md\ngit commit -m \"docs: caveat go install path until repo is public and tagged\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 3: Add `SECURITY.md` (P2)\n\n**Files:**\n- Create: `SECURITY.md`\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write the file**\n\n```markdown\n# Security Policy\n\n## Supported versions\n\n`kref` is pre-release and unversioned. Only the latest commit on the default\nbranch is supported. There is no back-porting yet.\n\n## Reporting a vulnerability\n\nPlease report suspected vulnerabilities privately to the maintainer at\n\u003cpeiriannydd@gmail.com\u003e rather than opening a public issue. Include repro steps\nand the commit SHA (`kref version`). Expect an acknowledgement within a few days.\n\n## Trust model\n\n`kref` stores knowledge as git objects under per-tier ref namespaces. The trust\nboundaries are:\n\n- **Tiers.** `private` (`refs/kref-private/*`) is structurally unpushable â€” no\n  remote can be configured for it, so it never leaves the machine.\n  `personal`/`shared` reach only the git remote you configure per tier.\n- **Ingest.** `kref ingest` scans markdown with gitleaks before storing. A secret\n  in an unmarked file quarantines the entry to `private`; a secret in a file\n  already mapped to a syncable tier fails closed (the entry is not updated).\n\n### Known limitations (attacker â†’ goal â†’ mitigation)\n\n- **Forgeable attribution.** Operations record a git identity but are *not*\n  cryptographically signed (git-bug v0.10.1 exposes no signing API). An attacker\n  with write access to a shared remote can author entries as someone else.\n  *Residual risk accepted for pre-release; tracked in the README limitations.*\n- **No encryption at rest.** The `private` tier stays local but is plaintext in\n  `.git`. An attacker with filesystem read access can read it. *Use full-disk\n  encryption; do not store secrets you would not put in `.git`.*\n- **Purge is not un-leak.** `kref purge --gc --push` deletes refs locally and on\n  the remote, but anything already fetched by a peer persists. *Rotate the\n  secret; treat any pushed secret as compromised.*\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add SECURITY.md\ngit commit -m \"docs: add SECURITY.md with trust model and disclosure contact\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 4: snake_case JSON on `entry.Snapshot` (P1)\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `internal/entry/snapshot.go`\n- Test: `cmd/kref/cli_test.go`\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write the failing test**\n\nAdd to `cmd/kref/cli_test.go`:\n\n```go\nvar _ = Describe(\"JSON schema\", func() {\n\tIt(\"uses snake_case keys consistently across add and show\", func() {\n\t\tdir := gitRepo()\n\t\trun(\"--dir\", dir, \"init\", \"--name\", \"T\", \"--email\", \"t@e.com\")\n\t\tout := run(\"--dir\", dir, \"add\", \"--title\", \"Schema\", \"--body\", \"b\")\n\t\tvar added struct {\n\t\t\tID string `json:\"id\"`\n\t\t}\n\t\tExpect(json.Unmarshal([]byte(out), \u0026added)).To(Succeed())\n\n\t\tshow := run(\"--dir\", dir, \"show\", added.ID, \"--json\")\n\t\tExpect(show).To(ContainSubstring(`\"id\":`))\n\t\tExpect(show).To(ContainSubstring(`\"created_at\":`))\n\t\tExpect(show).To(ContainSubstring(`\"created_by_email\":`))\n\t\tExpect(show).NotTo(ContainSubstring(`\"ID\":`))\n\t\tExpect(show).NotTo(ContainSubstring(`\"CreatedAt\":`))\n\t})\n})\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run it to verify it fails**\n\nRun: `KREF_GITLEAKS=$(go env GOPATH)/bin/gitleaks go test ./cmd/kref/ -run TestCLI 2\u003e\u00261 | tail`\nExpected: FAIL â€” `show` currently emits `\"ID\":`/`\"CreatedAt\":`.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Add json tags to the struct**\n\nReplace the `Snapshot` struct in `internal/entry/snapshot.go`:\n\n```go\n// Snapshot is the compiled, read-only view of an entry.\ntype Snapshot struct {\n\tID             entity.Id `json:\"id\"`\n\tKind           string    `json:\"kind\"`\n\tTitle          string    `json:\"title\"`\n\tStatus         string    `json:\"status\"` // open | active | accepted | superseded | deleted\n\tTier           string    `json:\"tier\"`   // set by the store from the namespace it was read under\n\tBody           string    `json:\"body\"`\n\tLinks          []Link    `json:\"links\"`\n\tDeleted        bool      `json:\"deleted\"`\n\tCreatedAt      time.Time `json:\"created_at\"`\n\tUpdatedAt      time.Time `json:\"updated_at\"`\n\tCreatedBy      string    `json:\"created_by\"`      // author display name, from the Create operation\n\tCreatedByEmail string    `json:\"created_by_email\"` // author email, from the Create operation\n}\n```\n\n(`Link` already has `json:\"to\"`/`json:\"type\"` tags â€” leave it.)\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run the test to verify it passes**\n\nRun: `gofmt -w internal/entry/snapshot.go \u0026\u0026 KREF_GITLEAKS=$(go env GOPATH)/bin/gitleaks go test ./cmd/kref/ -run TestCLI 2\u003e\u00261 | tail`\nExpected: PASS.\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add internal/entry/snapshot.go cmd/kref/cli_test.go\ngit commit -m \"fix(json): snake_case keys on Snapshot so list/show match add\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 5: one-line `--version` (P2)\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `cmd/kref/main.go:22`\n- Test: `cmd/kref/cli_test.go` (replace the existing `version output` spec)\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Update the failing test**\n\nIn `cmd/kref/cli_test.go`, replace the `Describe(\"version output\", â€¦)` block with:\n\n```go\nvar _ = Describe(\"version output\", func() {\n\tIt(\"emits a one-line `kref \u003cversion\u003e` for the flag and JSON for the subcommand\", func() {\n\t\tflag := run(\"--version\")\n\t\tExpect(flag).To(MatchRegexp(`^kref \\S+\\n$`))\n\t\tExpect(flag).NotTo(ContainSubstring(\"{\"))\n\n\t\tsub := run(\"version\")\n\t\tExpect(sub).To(ContainSubstring(`\"version\"`))\n\t})\n})\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run it to verify it fails**\n\nRun: `KREF_GITLEAKS=$(go env GOPATH)/bin/gitleaks go test ./cmd/kref/ -run TestCLI 2\u003e\u00261 | tail`\nExpected: FAIL â€” `--version` currently emits JSON.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Change the version template**\n\nIn `cmd/kref/main.go`, replace:\n\n```go\n\troot.SetVersionTemplate(\"{\\n  \\\"version\\\": \\\"{{.Version}}\\\"\\n}\\n\")\n```\n\nwith:\n\n```go\n\troot.SetVersionTemplate(\"kref {{.Version}}\\n\")\n```\n\n(`newVersionCmd` in `commands.go` is unchanged â€” `kref version` still emits JSON.)\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run the test to verify it passes**\n\nRun: `KREF_GITLEAKS=$(go env GOPATH)/bin/gitleaks go test ./cmd/kref/ -run TestCLI 2\u003e\u00261 | tail`\nExpected: PASS.\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add cmd/kref/main.go cmd/kref/cli_test.go\ngit commit -m \"fix(cli): --version prints a one-line 'kref \u003cversion\u003e'\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 6: grouped + ordered `--help` (help UX)\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `cmd/kref/main.go` (`newRootCmd`)\n- Test: `cmd/kref/cli_test.go`\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write the failing test**\n\nAdd to the `command aliases` Describe in `cmd/kref/cli_test.go` (or a new Describe):\n\n```go\nvar _ = Describe(\"help grouping\", func() {\n\tIt(\"renders titled groups with aliases inline\", func() {\n\t\tout := run(\"--help\")\n\t\tExpect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"Core Commands:\"))\n\t\tExpect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"Lifecycle Commands:\"))\n\t\tExpect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"Sync Commands:\"))\n\t\tExpect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"Setup Commands:\"))\n\t\tExpect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"add (new, create)\"))\n\t\t// Core appears before Sync (ordering, not alpha-sort).\n\t\tExpect(strings.Index(out, \"Core Commands:\")).To(BeNumerically(\"\u003c\", strings.Index(out, \"Sync Commands:\")))\n\t})\n})\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run it to verify it fails**\n\nRun: `KREF_GITLEAKS=$(go env GOPATH)/bin/gitleaks go test ./cmd/kref/ -run TestCLI 2\u003e\u00261 | tail`\nExpected: FAIL â€” no group titles yet.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Restructure `newRootCmd` for groups + order**\n\nReplace the body of `newRootCmd` in `cmd/kref/main.go` (the `root.AddCommand(...)` block and `return`) with:\n\n```go\n\tcobra.EnableCommandSorting = false\n\n\troot.AddGroup(\n\t\t\u0026cobra.Group{ID: \"core\", Title: \"Core Commands:\"},\n\t\t\u0026cobra.Group{ID: \"lifecycle\", Title: \"Lifecycle Commands:\"},\n\t\t\u0026cobra.Group{ID: \"sync\", Title: \"Sync Commands:\"},\n\t\t\u0026cobra.Group{ID: \"setup\", Title: \"Setup Commands:\"},\n\t\t\u0026cobra.Group{ID: \"additional\", Title: \"Additional Commands:\"},\n\t)\n\n\taddTo := func(group string, c *cobra.Command) {\n\t\tc.GroupID = group\n\t\troot.AddCommand(c)\n\t}\n\taddTo(\"core\", newAddCmd(\u0026dir))\n\taddTo(\"core\", newIngestCmd(\u0026dir))\n\taddTo(\"core\", newListCmd(\u0026dir))\n\taddTo(\"core\", newShowCmd(\u0026dir))\n\taddTo(\"lifecycle\", newRmCmd(\u0026dir))\n\taddTo(\"lifecycle\", newRestoreCmd(\u0026dir))\n\taddTo(\"lifecycle\", newPurgeCmd(\u0026dir))\n\taddTo(\"sync\", newRemoteCmd(\u0026dir))\n\taddTo(\"sync\", newSyncCmd(\u0026dir))\n\taddTo(\"setup\", newInitCmd(\u0026dir))\n\taddTo(\"setup\", newHooksCmd(\u0026dir))\n\taddTo(\"additional\", newVersionCmd())\n\n\troot.SetHelpCommandGroupID(\"additional\")\n\troot.SetCompletionCommandGroupID(\"additional\")\n\n\tlistAliasesInUsage(root)\n\treturn root\n```\n\n\u003e NOTE: `newRestoreCmd` is added in Task 12. Until then, comment out the\n\u003e `addTo(\"lifecycle\", newRestoreCmd(\u0026dir))` line (and the help test will still\n\u003e pass). Uncomment it in Task 12. If executing strictly in order, do Task 12\n\u003e before this step's `restore` line.\n\nSet `cobra.EnableCommandSorting = false` at the **top** of `newRootCmd`, before the `root` literal. `EnableCommandSorting` and `cobra` are already imported.\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run the test to verify it passes**\n\nRun: `KREF_GITLEAKS=$(go env GOPATH)/bin/gitleaks go test ./cmd/kref/ -run TestCLI 2\u003e\u00261 | tail`\nExpected: PASS. The `command aliases` map test still passes (aliases unchanged).\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Manual check**\n\nRun: `go build -o /tmp/kref ./cmd/kref \u0026\u0026 /tmp/kref --help`\nExpected: \"Core Commands:\" lists `add (new, create)`, `ingest (import)`, `list (ls)`, `show (cat, view, get)`; meta commands under \"Additional Commands:\".\n\n- [ ] **Step 6: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add cmd/kref/main.go cmd/kref/cli_test.go\ngit commit -m \"feat(cli): group and order commands in --help\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 7: short ids in human `list` (P2)\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `cmd/kref/commands.go` (`newListCmd` print loop)\n- Test: `cmd/kref/cli_test.go`\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write the failing test**\n\n```go\nvar _ = Describe(\"list short ids\", func() {\n\tIt(\"prints a 12-hex short id in human output but the full id in JSON\", func() {\n\t\tdir := gitRepo()\n\t\trun(\"--dir\", dir, \"init\", \"--name\", \"T\", \"--email\", \"t@e.com\")\n\t\trun(\"--dir\", dir, \"add\", \"--title\", \"Shorty\", \"--body\", \"b\")\n\t\thuman := run(\"--dir\", dir, \"list\")\n\t\tExpect(human).To(MatchRegexp(`(?m)^[0-9a-f]{12}  `))\n\t\tExpect(human).NotTo(MatchRegexp(`(?m)^[0-9a-f]{13}`))\n\t\tExpect(run(\"--dir\", dir, \"list\", \"--json\")).To(MatchRegexp(`[0-9a-f]{64}`))\n\t})\n})\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run it to verify it fails**\n\nRun: `KREF_GITLEAKS=$(go env GOPATH)/bin/gitleaks go test ./cmd/kref/ -run TestCLI 2\u003e\u00261 | tail`\nExpected: FAIL â€” human list prints the full 64-char id.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Shorten the id in the print loop**\n\nIn `cmd/kref/commands.go` `newListCmd`, replace the human print loop:\n\n```go\n\t\t\t\tfor _, it := range items {\n\t\t\t\t\tfmt.Fprintf(cmd.OutOrStdout(), \"%s  %-8s %-10s %s\\n\", it.ID, it.Kind, it.Status, it.Title)\n\t\t\t\t}\n```\n\nwith:\n\n```go\n\t\t\t\tfor _, it := range items {\n\t\t\t\t\tshort := it.ID.String()\n\t\t\t\t\tif len(short) \u003e 12 {\n\t\t\t\t\t\tshort = short[:12]\n\t\t\t\t\t}\n\t\t\t\t\tfmt.Fprintf(cmd.OutOrStdout(), \"%s  %-8s %-10s %s\\n\", short, it.Kind, it.Status, it.Title)\n\t\t\t\t}\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run the test to verify it passes**\n\nRun: `KREF_GITLEAKS=$(go env GOPATH)/bin/gitleaks go test ./cmd/kref/ -run TestCLI 2\u003e\u00261 | tail`\nExpected: PASS.\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add cmd/kref/commands.go cmd/kref/cli_test.go\ngit commit -m \"feat(cli): print 12-hex short ids in human list output\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 8: don't strand the lefthook banner on merge (P2)\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `internal/hooks/hooks.go` (`Merge`, + a small helper)\n- Test: `internal/hooks/hooks_test.go`\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write the failing test**\n\nAdd to `internal/hooks/hooks_test.go`:\n\n```go\nvar _ = Describe(\"Merge banner\", func() {\n\tIt(\"omits the managed banner when merging into an existing file\", func() {\n\t\texisting := []byte(\"pre-commit:\\n  commands:\\n    mine:\\n      run: make lint\\n\")\n\t\tout, err := hooks.Merge(existing, hooks.Render(\"/usr/bin/kref\", hooks.DefaultIngestPaths))\n\t\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tExpect(string(out)).NotTo(ContainSubstring(\"Managed by\"))\n\t\tExpect(string(out)).To(ContainSubstring(\"kref-sync-push\"))\n\t})\n\n\tIt(\"keeps the banner for a fresh install\", func() {\n\t\tout, err := hooks.Merge(nil, hooks.Render(\"/usr/bin/kref\", hooks.DefaultIngestPaths))\n\t\tExpect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())\n\t\tExpect(string(out)).To(ContainSubstring(\"Managed by\"))\n\t})\n})\n```\n\n\u003e This test uses `hooks.Render(\"/usr/bin/kref\", hooks.DefaultIngestPaths)`, the\n\u003e signature introduced in Task 9. If executing strictly in order, do Task 9\n\u003e first, or temporarily call the current `hooks.Render(\"/usr/bin/kref\")` and\n\u003e update it in Task 9.\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run it to verify it fails**\n\nRun: `go test ./internal/hooks/ 2\u003e\u00261 | tail`\nExpected: FAIL â€” merged output currently contains \"Managed by\" mid-file.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Strip leading comment lines before folding**\n\nIn `internal/hooks/hooks.go`, in `Merge`, after the empty-existing early return and before `yaml.Unmarshal([]byte(generated), \u0026genDoc)`, strip the banner from the *generated* text (the fresh-file path already returned with the banner intact):\n\n```go\n\tgenerated = stripLeadingComments(generated)\n```\n\nAdd the helper at the bottom of the file:\n\n```go\n// stripLeadingComments removes leading blank and `#` comment lines so a merge\n// does not graft kref's managed banner into the middle of the user's file. The\n// fresh-install path returns the banner-bearing text before this runs.\nfunc stripLeadingComments(s string) string {\n\tlines := strings.Split(s, \"\\n\")\n\ti := 0\n\tfor i \u003c len(lines) {\n\t\tt := strings.TrimSpace(lines[i])\n\t\tif t == \"\" || strings.HasPrefix(t, \"#\") {\n\t\t\ti++\n\t\t\tcontinue\n\t\t}\n\t\tbreak\n\t}\n\treturn strings.Join(lines[i:], \"\\n\")\n}\n```\n\n(`strings` is already imported in `hooks.go`.)\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Run the test to verify it passes**\n\nRun: `go test ./internal/hooks/ 2\u003e\u00261 | tail`\nExpected: PASS.\n\n- [ ] **Step 5: Commit**\n\n```bash\ngit add internal/hooks/hooks.go internal/hooks/hooks_test.go\ngit commit -m \"fix(hooks): drop managed banner when merging into existing config\"\n```\n\n---\n\n## Task 9: configurable hook ingest paths (P2)\n\n**Files:**\n- Modify: `internal/hooks/hooks.go` (`Render` signature + `DefaultIngestPaths`)\n- Modify: `cmd/kref/commands.go` (`newHooksCmd` install/print)\n- Modify: `internal/hooks/hooks_test.go` (existing `Render` callers)\n- Test: `cmd/kref/cli_test.go`\n\n- [ ] **Step 1: Write the failing test**\n\nAdd to `cmd/kref/cli_test.go` `kref hooks` Describe:\n\n```go\n\tIt(\"honors --ingest-path overrides\", func() {\n\t\tout := run(\"hooks\", \"print\", \"--ingest-path\", \"foo\", \"--ingest-path\", \"bar\")\n\t\tExpect(out).To(ContainSubstring(\"-- foo bar\"))\n\t\tExpect(out).NotTo(ContainSubstring(\"openspec\"))\n\t})\n\n\tIt(\"uses the default paths when no override is given\", func() {\n\t\tExpect(run(\"hooks\", \"print\")).To(ContainSubstring(\"docs/superpowers/plans specs .specify openspec\"))\n\t})\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 2: Run it to verify it fails**\n\nRun: `KREF_GITLEAKS=$(go env GOPATH)/bin/gitleaks go test ./cmd/kref/ -run TestCLI 2\u003e\u00261 | tail`\nExpected: FAIL â€” `--ingest-path` flag does not exist.\n\n- [ ] **Step 3: Parameterize `Render`**\n\nIn `internal/hooks/hooks.go`, add the default and change `Render`:\n\n```go\n// DefaultIngestPaths are the directories the post-commit hook watches for\n// changed markdown when no --ingest-path override is supplied.\nvar DefaultIngestPaths = []string{\"docs/superpowers/plans\", \"specs\", \".specify\", \"openspec\"}\n\n// Render returns a lefthook configuration wiring kref to git lifecycle events.\n// krefPath is the absolute path to the kref binary (os.Executable at install time)\n// so the hooks work even when kref is not on PATH. ingestPaths are the\n// directories the post-commit hook scans for changed markdown.\nfunc Render(krefPath string, ingestPaths []string) string {\n\tif len(ingestPaths) == 0 {\n\t\tingestPaths = DefaultIngestPaths\n\t}\n\treturn fmt.Sprintf(`# Managed by `+\"`kref hooks install`\"+`. Run by lefthook (https://lefthook.dev).\npost-merge:\n  commands:\n    kref-sync-pull:\n      run: %[1]s sync pull\npost-checkout:\n  commands:\n    kref-sync-pull:\n      run: %[1]s sync pull\npre-push:\n  commands:\n    kref-sync-push:\n      run: %[1]s sync push\npost-commit:\n  commands:\n    kref-ingest:\n      files: git diff-tree --no-commit-id --name-only -r HEAD -- %[2]s\n      glob: \"*.md\"\n      run: %[1]s ingest --skip-missing {files}\n`, krefPath, strings.Join(ingestPaths, \" \"))\n}\n```\n\n- [ ] **Step 4: Update the CLI to add the flag**\n\nIn `cmd/kref/commands.go` `newHooksCmd`, add a shared flag var and wire both subcommands. Replace the `install`/`printCmd` construction so each reads an `ingestPaths` slice:\n\n```go\nfunc newHooksCmd(dir *string) *cobra.Command {\n\tc := \u0026cobra.Command{Use: \"hooks\", Short: \"Manage git lifecycle hooks (lefthook)\"}\n\tvar force bool\n\tvar ingestPaths []string\n\tinstall := \u0026cobra.Command{\n\t\tUse:   \"install\",\n\t\tShort: \"Write a lefthook.yml wiring kref sync/ingest to git events\",\n\t\tRunE: func(cmd *cobra.Command, _ []string) error {\n\t\t\texe, err := os.Executable()\n\t\t\tif err != nil {\n\t\t\t\treturn err\n\t\t\t}\n\t\t\tgenerated := hooks.Render(exe, ingestPaths)\n\t\t\tpath := filepath.Join(*dir, hooks.InstallPath)\n\t\t\texisting, statErr := os.ReadFile(path)\n\t\t\tif statErr != nil \u0026\u0026 !os.IsNotExist(statErr) {\n\t\t\t